<DOC><DOCNO> AP881001-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 1719EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-01 0246</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0252</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Scattered Over Southeastern Quarter Of Nation</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Showers and thunderstorms developed Saturday along a weakweather disturbance moving slowly across the Mississippi Valley,and over the Southeast and the southern Plains.   The showers and thunderstorms associated with the weakdisturbance extended from the central Gulf Coast to Indiana,western Ohio and eastern Wisconsin.   Thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain and a flash floodwatch was issued for southwestern Alabama.   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered along the southernAtlantic Coast, and across central Oklahoma and north-centralTexas. A thunderstorm in central Oklahoma produced hail thediameter of nickels southwest of the town of Minco.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 96 at Palm Springs,Calif. Saturday morning's low was 17 at Gunnison, Colo.   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastahead of a cold front from the Gulf Coast region to the northernAtlantic Coast states and the Great Lakes region.   Highs only in the 50s were predicted from North Dakota to UpperMichigan; below 70 from Montana through the northern and centralPlains to northern New England; in the 80s across much of thenation west of the Rockies, and across southern Texas, the centralGulf Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast states; and in the 90sin the desert Southwest and the valleys of southern California,with readings above 100 degrees at some locations.</TEXT></DOC>